5. Jensen's Inequality\
5.1 Convex Functions Definition\
Definition:\'a0A function\'a0$g(x)$\'a0is convex on interval\'a0$S$\'a0if, for any\'a0$x_1, x_2 \\in S$\'a0and\'a0$\\alpha \\in [0, 1]$, we have:\
\
$g(\\alpha x_1 + (1-\\alpha)x_2) \\le \\alpha g(x_1) + (1-\\alpha)g(x_2)$\
5.2 Jensen's Theorem and Intuition\
Theorem (Jensen's Inequality):\'a0If\'a0$g(x)$\'a0is convex on an interval\'a0$S$\'a0and\'a0$X$\'a0takes values in\'a0$S$, then:\
\
$g(E[X]) \\le E[g(X)]$\
Interpretation:\'a0Averaging first yields a smaller value; applying the convex function first yields a larger value.\'a0Convex functions push expectation upwards.\
We already know variance is non-negative ($Var(X) = E[X^2] - E[X]^2 \\ge 0 \\Rightarrow E[X^2] \\ge E[X]^2$).\'a0Jensen's inequality generalises this: for any positive random variable\'a0$X$\'a0and\'a0$a \\in \\mathbb\{R\}$,\'a0$E[X^a] \\ge E[X]^a$.\
5.3 Worked Example: Verifying Jensen's Inequality Numerically\
Problem:\'a0Let\'a0$X = 1$\'a0with probability 0.5, and\'a0$X = 3$\'a0with probability 0.5.\'a0Verify Jensen's for\'a0$g(x) = x^2$.\'a0\
Step 1:\'a0Compute expectation.\'a0$E[X] = 0.5(1) + 0.5(3) = 2$.\
\
Apply function after averaging:\'a0$g(E[X]) = (2)^2 = 4$.\
\
Apply function first:\'a0$E[g(X)] = 0.5(1^2) + 0.5(3^2) = 5$.\
\
Result:\'a0Since\'a0$4 \\le 5$, the inequality holds.\
